50|$|The AmigaOS has a {{dynamically}} sized <b>RAM</b> <b>disk,</b> which resizes itself automatically {{to accommodate}} its contents. Starting with AmigaOS 2.x, operating system configuration files were {{loaded into the}} <b>RAM</b> <b>disk</b> on boot, greatly speeding operating system usage. Other files could be copied to the <b>RAM</b> <b>disk</b> like any standard device for quick modification and retrieval. Also beginning in AmigaOS 2.x, the <b>RAM</b> <b>disk</b> supported file-change notification, which was mostly used to monitor configuration files for changes.|$|E
