50|$|Starting with AmigaOS 1.3, {{there is}} also a fixed-capacity {{recoverable}} <b>RAM</b> <b>disk,</b> which functions as a standard <b>RAM</b> <b>disk</b> but can maintain its contents on soft restart. It is commonly called the RAD disk after its default device name, and it {{can be used as a}} boot disk (with boot sector). Previously, a recoverable <b>RAM</b> <b>disk,</b> commonly called the ASDG RRD or VD0, was introduced in 1987; at first, it was locked to ASDG expansion memory products. Later, the ASDG RRD was added to the Fred Fish series of freeware, shareware, and public domain software (disks 58 and 241).|$|E
